<font color="#FF0000">REPLY TO &quot;MR.&quot; EDWARD RAMON</font><br>
<tt>Thu Aug 28 21:50:54 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Edward, a quick thought. You say the war did not end for you. &quot;I wish it would, I wish it could..&quot;. So do I brother, for your inside peace.  BUT  you must understand that for alot of us it did end.  For many of you with lasting scars, both mental and physical, ptsd to missing limbs or worse, the war is faught everyday you get out of bed. I understand that.  I know what you face everyday. That is the professional side of me, which I left at the door of this site.<br><br>
I need you to understand the other side, Ed, that the war ended for others. Not out of moral victory, or physical survival, it just ended. The media got tired of it and it ended. The body bag count got boring for Ma and Pa T.V. and it was dropped.  For you, and guys like you, PTSD or whatever, it never ended. I UNDERSTAND THAT. But, I need you to understand that others are different. Others let it die. Someday you will be able to.  I hope so. I will be your brother and your friend until that time, and if you want, beyond. I understand. That is all I can offer you. I was not in the jungle, I am not a good ammo loader. But, I am not a runner either, be it from the draft board or the cong. My words may get scrambled, but I am a man of those words. I will bare with you until hell freezes over, because I respect that you think. THINK. That is the magic word that seperates us from the animals and creatures that go Lurch in the night. Keep thinking Ed. Let me keep pushing you as you push me. Together, we can go into that dark night. Together we can win.  You are a vet, I am a protestor, yet the tears that swim in my eyes are that for a brother, not an enemy.<br><br>

<p><code>-- shrink4u@mail.quik.com  (doc) </code><p>


